Said it before and we‚Äôll say it agan... it‚Äôs Miuccia‚Äôs world, we just live in it. It was a jaw-dropping @prada show, but you don‚Äôt have to take our word for it. A few looks in, and you could hear the mounting chatter in the audience... likely the murmurs of deep desire that few designers can ignite. Personally speaking, we had a visceral reaction that this would be one of ùòµùò©ùò∞ùò¥ùò¶ Prada collections... that rare agenda-setting vision that sends the entire industry into a tizzy.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
There‚Äôs always a duality in the Prada muse... the feminine vs. masculine, retro vs the ultra-modern, and ‚Äúugly‚Äù vs chic. In this collection, the strength and fragility of the feminine sparkled, sometimes through strong, heavy suiting and other times in generous doses of embellishment. But why should you have to choose between either? A couple of our favorite looks layered banal office wear under flirty separates with beaded fringe‚Äîthe ultimate boss lady.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
There‚Äôs also plenty of references to Prada‚Äôs archives that will leave fanatics satisfied. Tiny antique-feeling miniaudieres, harkening back to Prada way before Miuccia, were clutched in hand, dangled from necklaces and even turned into clever belt buckles. New riffs on iconic pieces like the FW09 gladiator skirts and SS08 pyjama separates have us wondering if they‚Äôre better the second time around... like a cover song you hate to admit is better than the original.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
It all ended with a thunderous applause... louder than the usual. Lord, grant us the balls to start the standing ovation next season, because this surely deserved it.

It shouldn‚Äôt be down to the models to have to refuse wearing blatantly racist accessories on the runway, especially not in a show thrown by an institution like @fitnyc. In an alumni show celebrating their 75th anniversary, MFA graduate Junkai Huang showed a collection that was meant to highlight the ‚Äúugly features of the body‚Äù. The choice of exaggerated bright red fake lips and ‚Äúmonkey ears‚Äù, as well as the school‚Äôs response, are leaving us shaking our heads.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Nearing a breakdown, African-American model Amy Lefevre (@lefevrediary ) spoke up about the accessories, but was told by staff it was ‚Äúok to be uncomfortable for only 45 seconds‚Äù. It‚Äôs one thing when it‚Äôs a pair of tricky heels, but quite another when you‚Äôre made up to look like racist caricatures from the not-so-distant past. Multiple complaints had been made in the days leading up to the show as well, with several people objecting. One anonymous student who was witness backstage, said the show‚Äôs producer @richardthornn told the group to ‚Äúback down and get away‚Äù when they brought up the issue again. The accessories didn‚Äôt end up making it onto Lefevre, but that didn‚Äôt stop them from going down the runway on other models.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
In a statement to the NY Post, FIT president Dr. Joyce F. Brown emphasized allowing the students the ‚Äúfreedom to craft their own personal and unique artistic perspectives as designers, to be even what some would consider to be provocative‚Äù, but said they would investigate further.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
In a time when luxury brands are taking swift action by pulling offensive products and implementing diversity councils in response to similar scandals, it‚Äôs a shame to see a learning institution dragging their feet. Shouldn‚Äôt they be the ones broadening insights for the ones who will lead fashion in the future and not reinforcing the same aspects that have made the industry notoriously problematic? ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä

Inside a chilly wing at The Africa Center this morning, @Area babes, both guests and models, turned up the heat for FW20. Hometown heroes Beckett Fogg and Piotrek Panszczyk served us some Madame Gr√®s meets Eiko Ishioka inspo, hitting a soft spot for the fashion/film nerd in us.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Hints of the French couturier‚Äôs masterful draping met details of the famed costume designer‚Äôs avant-garde vision, the best of which were bodysuits with graphic forms that torqued around the shoulder‚Äîthey‚Äôd be equally fit for a film heroine or fashion week‚Äôs finest peacocks. More takes on Madame Gr√®s saw her interwoven draping rendered in suiting wool and strands of crystal cup chain. Their signature crystal-work felt extra fresh when edged around spotty cutouts... in particular a boxy camel wool coat that looked like someone had given a moth-eaten hand me down a major upcycle.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Wedged between was a singular homage to the iconic VR bodysuits designed by Ishioka for the 2000 sci-fi film The Cell. In leotard form with thigh high boots, it‚Äôd be quite the nostalgia trip should J.Lo choose to bless us all by wearing it. The finale looks stunned no less. Gathered volumes and articulated cuts ballooned into a parade of finale looks that left us literally seeing hearts.

‚ÄúArchetypal couture‚Äù read the show notes for @maisonvalentino . What does it look like when decades of the storied tradition are reinterpreted for the 21st century? @pppiccioli shows us with aplomb and leaves absolutely nothing to be desired.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
The grand flourishes of the Belle √âpoque,  the bodycon silhouettes of the 1950s (think Charles James), space-age textures, and the dramatic 80s poufs that have become a Valentino signature, were complemented by looks that were minimal and pure... Pierpaolo giving us a glimpse into his dream of the future.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
If past collections focused much on the froth, there was a new sharpness to this collection and a sensuality we haven‚Äôt seen before with all the figure-hugging silhouettes and skin on display like the embellished cutouts that edged along the side of the body.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
We could go on, but such perfection rarely demands an explanation. Highly recommend watching this entire video.

@acnestudios x AI design assistants?‚Ä¢The FW20 men‚Äôs and women‚Äôs collections took place simultaneously last night, split by a divider in the underground space beneath the Louvre.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
If any of the looks were somewhat indescribable, it was due to some clever technology. In a collaboration with artist @robbie.exe , who uses AI as a medium, thousands of archive Acne looks were fed through software. Not every machine we build is perfect, though. Limitations and programmed glitches resulted in aesthetics not bound by the practicalities and preconceptions of garments as we know them, and that was the point.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
There were certain things Barrat‚Äôs neural network recognized about the clothing, but Jonny Johansson ran with the things machine couldn‚Äôt understand like fabric textures, buttons, and varying hemlines/closures. Despite the AI assistance, the output still resulted in Acne‚Äôs signature of off-kilter cool.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Women‚Äôs had a more straightforward narrative, using fabric as a jumping off point and focusing on treating fancy fabrics like everyday ones - jeans cut from rich jacquards, day dresses in yards and yards of sumptuous  velvets and upholstery fabric suiting. Languid layered looks in mixed jersey and draped flared pants that pooled around the model‚Äôs feet were especially noteworthy.

It takes skill to make a strong collection in so many neutral shades. @jacquemus threw his blowout anniversary show last season, but this season felt more like the Jacquemus we all grew to love (hatgate aside) and spurred so many others to copy.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Maybe it‚Äôs the fact that it took place on Simon‚Äôs birthday (HBD Simon üéÇ ) that there was a sort of greatest-hits feeling to this outing. The now-established Jacquemus signatures were on full display, from the flirty ruched-to-the-hip dresses paired with sculptural heels, boxy blazers, countryside workwear separates, and bags from big to small (and smaller).
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
And can we talk about that cast? Supers galore... Laetitia, Doutzen, Adut, Liu Wen, les Hadids and many more made their turns on a giant, brightly lit white catwalk. Sparing any ambient scenography, it was the maximum impact the collection deserved.
